from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

# Select the categorical columns for label encoding
categorical_columns = ['sex', 'school']

# Create a dictionary to store the mapping of encoded values
encoding_mapping = {}

# Apply label encoding to each categorical column
for column in categorical_columns:
    # Create an instance of LabelEncoder
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    
    # Fit and transform the column with label encoding
    encoded_values = label_encoder.fit_transform(df[column])
    
    # Update the column in the DataFrame with encoded values
    df[column] = encoded_values
    
    # Store the mapping of encoded values for the column
    encoding_mapping[column] = dict(zip(label_encoder.classes_, label_encoder.transform(label_encoder.classes_)))

# Print the mapping of encoded values for 'sex' column
print("Mapping of encoded values for 'sex' column:")
print(encoding_mapping['sex'])

# Print the mapping of encoded values for 'school' column
print("Mapping of encoded values for 'school' column:")
print(encoding_mapping['school'])

Mapping of encoded values for 'sex' column:
{'F': 0, 'M': 1}
Mapping of encoded values for 'school' column:
{'GP': 0, 'MS': 1}

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define the discrete G3 for visualization
discrete_variables = ['G3', 'G1', 'G2', 'Medu', 'health', 'failures','studytime']
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define the bins and labels for 'G1' and 'G2' columns
bins = [0, 10, 12, 14, 16, 20]
labels = [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]

# Create the subplot grid
num_rows = 3
num_cols = 3
fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, num_cols, figsize=(16, 10))
axes = axes.flatten()

# Iterate over the discrete variables and plot the bar chart for each variable
for i, variable in enumerate(discrete_variables):
    plt.subplot(num_rows, num_cols, i+1)
    if variable == 'G1' or variable == 'G2' or variable == 'G3':
        counts = pd.cut(df[variable], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False).value_counts().sort_index()
        plt.title(variable + "_classifcation", fontsize=12)
    else:
        counts = df[variable].value_counts().sort_index()
        plt.title(variable, fontsize=12)
    labels = counts.index.tolist()
    colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'cyan', 'orange']
    plt.bar(labels, counts, color=colors)
    plt.xlabel(variable)
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    
plt.subplot(num_rows, num_cols, 8)
plt.hist(df['age'], bins=10, color= 'g')
plt.title("Age", fontsize=12)
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel('Frequency')

# Adjust layout and spacing
plt.tight_layout()

# Display the plot
plt.show()

ax2.legend(title='Final Grade (G3)')
ax2.set_xlabel('Sex')
ax2.set_ylabel('Percentage')
ax2.set_title('Proportion of Final Grade by Sex')

2.3 Is there a relationship between the number of study hours (studytime) and final grades (G3) for students who have failed at least one course (failures > 0) compared to those who haven't failed any courses (failures = 0)?¶

In [34]:
import scipy.stats as stats

# Filter the dataframe for students who have failed at least one course
failed_students = df[df['failures'] > 0]

# Filter the dataframe for students who haven't failed any courses
non_failed_students = df[df['failures'] == 0]

# Calculate the average study hours and final grades for the two groups
failed_avg_studytime = failed_students['studytime'].mean()
failed_avg_grade = failed_students['G3'].mean()

non_failed_avg_studytime = non_failed_students['studytime'].mean()
non_failed_avg_grade = non_failed_students['G3'].mean()

# Perform a statistical test (e.g., t-test) to compare the two groups
t_statistic, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(failed_students['studytime'], non_failed_students['studytime'])

# Print the results
print("Average Study Hours for Failed Students: ", failed_avg_studytime)
print("Average Final Grade for Failed Students: ", failed_avg_grade)
print("Average Study Hours for Non-Failed Students: ", non_failed_avg_studytime)
print("Average Final Grade for Non-Failed Students: ", non_failed_avg_grade)
print("T-Statistic: ", t_statistic)
print("P-value: ", p_value)

Average Study Hours for Non-Failed Students:  2.1032258064516127

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

dt1 = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=best_params['max_depth'], criterion=best_params['criterion'])
dt_trained1 = dt1.fit(X_train1, y_train1)
y_pred1 = dt_trained1.predict(X_test1)

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'n_neighbors': range(1, 100),
    'weights': ['uniform', 'distance'],
    'p': [1, 2]
}

# Create an instance of KNeighborsClassifier
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()

# Perform grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(knn, param_grid, scoring='accuracy', cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train1, y_train1)

# Retrieve the best parameters and best model
best_score = grid_search.best_score_
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_

print('best_params:', best_params)

# Use the best model for predictions

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'n_neighbors': range(1, 100),
    'weights': ['uniform', 'distance'],
    'p': [1, 2]
}

# Create an instance of KNeighborsClassifier
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()

# Perform grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(knn, param_grid, scoring='accuracy', cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train3, y_train3)

# Retrieve the best parameters and best model
best_score = grid_search.best_score_
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_

print('best_score:', best_score)
print('best_params:', best_params)

# Use the best model for predictions
y_pred3 = best_model.predict(X_test3)
